From: Olivier Cochard-Labbe <olivier@FreeBSD.org>
Subject: [PATCH] tun(4): refuse if_clone destroy of an in-use device with EBUSY

tun_destroy() is reached two ways:

 1. via tun_clone_destroy() (may_intr=true), which is called from
    if_clone_destroyif() with ifnet_detach_sxlock held exclusively
    (sys/net/if_clone.c:480). This is the `ifconfig tunN destroy` path.

 2. via tun_uninit() (may_intr=false) at module unload time. This path
    does not hold ifnet_detach_sxlock.

In path 1, if the tun device currently has an open consumer (tun_busy
!= 0), the existing code sets TUN_DYING and parks in cv_wait_sig() on
tun_cv waiting for the consumer's close(2). With the global
ifnet_detach_sxlock held exclusively, every other ifnet-clone destroy
on the host (including the chain reaction into tuntap_prison_remove ->
if_clone_detach from `jail -R`) immediately blocks in _sx_xlock_hard.

Reproducer (kernel wedges, only a reboot recovers):

    ifconfig tun create                  # -> tun1
    sleep 9999 < /dev/tun1 &
    ifconfig tun1 destroy                # never returns
    ifconfig <anything-else> destroy     # blocks in _sx_xlock_hard

cv_wait_sig() is nominally interruptible, but SIGKILL to the ifconfig
caller does not break the wait in practice, presumably because the
process is parked in a syscall holding kernel resources.

Refuse the destroy in path 1 with EBUSY instead of waiting. This
matches the spirit of other "destroy a parent of an in-use child"
checks. Module unload (path 2) keeps the existing wait-for-close
semantics because the unload cannot proceed past in-use devices and
is not holding any global sx lock.

Confirmed in a vmcore from a 16.0-CURRENT GENERIC (debug) kernel:
DEADLKRES panics naming the waiter ifconfig thread, and
ifnet_detach_sxlock.sx_lock decodes to the holder td which is the
ifconfig parked in tun_destroy -> cv_wait_sig.

PR:		<to be filed>
Reported by:	wedge on bigone 2026-05-26, dump under /var/crash
---
diff --git sys/net/if_tuntap.c sys/net/if_tuntap.c
index a1ef2541ffba..1a7a35779fa6 100644
--- sys/net/if_tuntap.c
+++ sys/net/if_tuntap.c
@@ -646,7 +646,6 @@ tunfree(struct epoch_context *ctx)
 static int
 tun_destroy(struct tuntap_softc *tp, bool may_intr)
 {
-	int error;

 	TUN_LOCK(tp);

@@ -655,18 +654,31 @@ tun_destroy(struct tuntap_softc *tp, bool may_intr)
 	 * a result of the last close, which we'll allow.
 	 */
 	MPASS((tp->tun_flags & (TUN_DYING | TUN_TRANSIENT)) != TUN_DYING);
+
+	/*
+	 * If our caller is willing to be interrupted (i.e. we are reached from
+	 * if_clone_destroy(), holding ifnet_detach_sxlock exclusively) and
+	 * the device currently has an open consumer, refuse the destroy with
+	 * EBUSY rather than parking on tun_cv with the global sx lock held.
+	 * Waiting here is unbounded: tun_busy only drops to 0 when the
+	 * consumer close(2)s the device, and a process holding the fd open
+	 * in select(2) (e.g. openvpn) will not do so on demand. The result
+	 * is that every subsequent ifnet-clone destroy on the host wedges in
+	 * _sx_xlock_hard, with only a reboot to recover.
+	 *
+	 * Module unload (may_intr == false, from tun_uninit() outside the
+	 * ifnet-clone path) still waits, because the unload itself cannot
+	 * proceed past in-use devices and is not holding any global sx lock.
+	 */
+	if (may_intr && tp->tun_busy != 0) {
+		TUN_UNLOCK(tp);
+		return (EBUSY);
+	}
+
 	tp->tun_flags |= TUN_DYING;
-	error = 0;
 	while (tp->tun_busy != 0) {
-		if (may_intr)
-			error = cv_wait_sig(&tp->tun_cv, &tp->tun_mtx);
-		else
-			cv_wait(&tp->tun_cv, &tp->tun_mtx);
-		if (error != 0 && tp->tun_busy != 0) {
-			tp->tun_flags &= ~TUN_DYING;
-			TUN_UNLOCK(tp);
-			return (error);
-		}
+		MPASS(!may_intr);
+		cv_wait(&tp->tun_cv, &tp->tun_mtx);
 	}
 	TUN_UNLOCK(tp);
